post_text:
As a courtesy, we wanted to pass along some information from a national news story regarding an online social media "challenge" that could impact your child's health. There has been a TikTok video circulating in the past few months concerning the Benadryl Challenge. This challenge involves teens taking large amounts of Benadryl. A teen in Oklahoma recently died after taking large amounts of Benadryl. We have no indication at all about any students in our community participating in this challenge, but thought you as parents and guardians should have this information. The link below is to Banner Health's statement regarding the phenomenon, as well as phone numbers to the American Association of Poison Control Centers.

post_text: 2/3 benchmarks set by ADHS for safely reopening schools are being met! We still need 2 weeks of positivity rate to be below 7% . This currently sits at 9.4% per the available data, which decreased from 10.9% the previous week. Do consider though that latest reports are much lower than this, so if the next 2 weeks are below 7% which looks very possible, we will be able to open for in-person learning on September 8 as planned. Keep doing your part and we will hopefully see you back on campus soon!üíú

post_text:
Governor Ducey and Superintendent Hoffman just released the following joint statement:

‚ÄúIn alignment with yesterday‚Äôs updated federal guidance, today we are announcing the extension of school closures through the remainder of the school year. Today‚Äôs announcement is intended to give parents and educators as much certainty as possible so they can plan and make decisions. While this isn‚Äôt the outcome any of us wanted, we are grateful for the partnership of schools around the state, who have stepped up to offer virtual and take-home learning opportunities for our students. These efforts are crucial, and we recognize that schools are making every effort possible to continue providing instruction during closures. We also thank our legislative partners for passing legislation ensuring all educators and staff see no disruption in pay. Our number one priority will continue to be health and safety, and we will continue to work closely with public health officials to make the best decisions for kids, families, and our school communities.‚Äù

post_text:
Ryan, Dylan & Odessa competed in the Queen's Crown chess tournament on Saturday and made SCDS proud! Dylan came in second overall in the K-6 Under 600 division winning 4 out of 5 rounds!!

Ryan and Odessa each won three of their games which earned them the third place team trophy out of 27 teams in their division!!

Ryan and Odessa delivered the team trophy to the office before school this morning.

CONGRATULATIONS!
